1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,614
This presentation describes polynomial input preconditioning
for zero-shot time-series forecasting.

2
00:00:06,614 --> 00:00:14,884
The key preliminary is Universal Sequence Preconditioning,
proposed by Marsden and Hazan for online prediction in
marginally stable linear dynamical systems.

3
00:00:14,884 --> 00:00:26,304
Their insight is that instead of asking a learner to infer a
potentially large hidden state directly, one can first
transform the observed sequence with a fixed polynomial
convolution.

4
00:00:26,304 --> 00:00:34,180
Chebyshev-style coefficients are useful because they uniformly
damp the difficult modes of the hidden dynamics across a broad
spectral range.

5
00:00:34,180 --> 00:00:42,844
The intuition for this project is to use that same fixed,
theory-guided signal as information given to a patch-based
transformer before tokenization.

6
00:00:42,844 --> 00:00:48,931
The starting point is a common design in modern time-series
foundation models like Moirai 2.0.

7
00:00:48,931 --> 00:00:57,857
These models split the input sequence into fixed-length
patches, embed each patch independently, and then run a
transformer over the resulting tokens.

8
00:00:57,857 --> 00:01:05,161
This is efficient, but it creates a bottleneck: before
attention, each token only sees its own local patch.

9
00:01:05,161 --> 00:01:10,842
If important structure spans multiple patches, the transformer
has to discover that structure later.

10
00:01:10,842 --> 00:01:15,966
My idea is to expose a small amount of cross-patch information
before tokenization.

11
00:01:15,966 --> 00:01:20,301
I use a fixed polynomial convolution motivated by Universal
Sequence Preconditioning.

12
00:01:20,301 --> 00:01:31,730
In the default setting, the residual channel is r sub t equals
negative x sub t minus thirty two, plus one eighth times x sub
t minus sixty four.

13
00:01:31,730 --> 00:01:40,007
This is computed from the normalized input series, split into
patches, and concatenated alongside the raw input patch and
observation mask.

14
00:01:40,007 --> 00:01:47,101
The only architectural change is that the first projection
layer gets wider, from two patch channels to three.

15
00:01:47,101 --> 00:01:51,042
The transformer decoder, output head, and forecast target are
unchanged.

16
00:01:51,042 --> 00:01:58,136
The overhead is only twelve thousand parameters, or about zero
point one one percent of Moirai 2.0 Small.

17
00:01:58,136 --> 00:02:01,130
This diagram shows the full architectural change.

18
00:02:01,130 --> 00:02:13,532
The orange boxes are the new parts: compute the Chebyshev
residual, optionally apply hint dropout during training,
concatenate the raw input, mask, and residual, and widen the
input projection.

19
00:02:13,532 --> 00:02:20,374
Everything inside the Moirai 2.0 decoder block and the
autoregressive quantile output head stays the same.

20
00:02:20,374 --> 00:02:25,272
The main result is on GIFT-Eval, which has ninety-seven
dataset-by-horizon forecasting configurations.

21
00:02:25,272 --> 00:02:33,843
Across five seeds, the preconditioned model improves
geometric-mean normalized MASE by two point nine percent over
the Moirai 2.0 Small baseline.

22
00:02:33,843 --> 00:02:43,230
After averaging each configuration across seeds, it wins
seventy-two of ninety-seven configurations, with a paired
sign-test p-value below ten to the minus five.

23
00:02:43,230 --> 00:02:45,679
The important control is capacity matching.

24
00:02:45,679 --> 00:02:54,658
I trained the same widened architecture with a zero third
channel and with a duplicate of the input as the third
channel.

25
00:02:54,658 --> 00:03:02,004
Those controls do not reproduce the gain, so the improvement
comes from the polynomial content of the channel.

26
00:03:02,004 --> 00:03:05,855
I also tested whether the result transfers beyond GIFT-Eval.

27
00:03:05,855 --> 00:03:18,265
On FEV-Bench, an independent benchmark with one hundred
forecasting tasks, the same method improves MASE by two point
nine percent and scaled quantile loss by three point one
percent.

28
00:03:18,265 --> 00:03:23,827
In ablations, every tested Chebyshev degree from two through
seven improves over baseline.

29
00:03:23,827 --> 00:03:30,674
Fixed Chebyshev coefficients also outperform learned
coefficient vectors initialized either from Chebyshev
coefficients or from zero.

30
00:03:30,674 --> 00:03:33,135
Finally, the effect grows with training.

31
00:03:33,135 --> 00:03:42,981
At one hundred thousand steps, the MASE improvement reaches
three point nine percent, and the preconditioned model has
lower cross-seed variance than the baseline.

32
00:03:42,981 --> 00:03:50,776
The gains are also largest on longer-horizon forecasting
tasks, where the dropout version is more robust during
autoregressive decoding.

33
00:03:50,776 --> 00:03:57,260
The takeaway is that foundation-model performance does not
only come from scaling model size.

34
00:03:57,260 --> 00:04:06,523
A small, fixed, theory-guided transformation placed before
tokenization can improve zero-shot forecasting while leaving
the transformer itself almost completely unchanged.

35
00:04:06,523 --> 00:04:13,470
For time series models, this suggests a practical path toward
more accurate and parameter-efficient forecasters.
